# Pin the invariant register notes to LF. The guard checkers
# (scripts/verify-invariant-guards.mjs, scripts/verify-invariant-frontmatter.mjs)
# match frontmatter with a /^---\n/ regex that silently skips a CRLF file — so a
# CRLF note is an invisible governance hole on Windows checkouts (core.autocrlf=true).
# Committing these as LF keeps the checkers honest regardless of the local working tree.
docs/architecture/invariants/*.md text eol=lf

# Same LF pin for the sibling registers + the pure-Node guard scripts that parse
# them (verify:tripwires, verify:parity, verify:ai-native). A CRLF frontmatter is a
# silent governance hole; a CRLF .mjs is harmless but kept consistent.
docs/architecture/tripwires/*.md text eol=lf
docs/architecture/parity/*.md text eol=lf
docs/architecture/assistant-coverage.md text eol=lf
scripts/*.mjs text eol=lf
scripts/lib/*.mjs text eol=lf

# Vintrace API knowledge base (specs + generated KB) — keep LF for clean diffs.
vintrace-docs/api/** text eol=lf

# Claude Code workflow scripts (/bug-triage, /health-check, /health-remediate).
# The Workflow tool inlines the script into its approval dialog and REFUSES any
# file containing CR — "script contains control characters that would be hidden in
# the approval dialog" — even when invoked by scriptPath. So on a Windows checkout
# (core.autocrlf=true) these skills are simply unlaunchable until someone strips the
# CRs by hand. The blobs are already LF; it is the CHECKOUT that reintroduces them,
# which is why this cannot be fixed by committing the file: with autocrlf on, git
# reports no diff at all for an LF-ified working copy. This pin is the only fix.
.claude/workflows/*.js text eol=lf
